{
  "texts": [
    "To get the spatial dependent location density we use the most popular spatial analysis technique called kernel density estimation (KDE).",
    "KDE is a statistical method and a non-parametric way to estimate the probability density function of a random feature and correlates it to features in its neighborhood.",
    "By correlating each feature with a kernel function and summing up all the weighted overlapping regions of the kernel we get the probability density as a level of spatial distribution of nuclei density.",
    "The kernel is chosen as a multivariate gauss function with a fixed bandwidth of 0.2 for all images to ensure comparability of lobules from different sections among each other.",
    "The bandwith was empirically determined by analyzing 3 of the control samples by using the scott algorithm for bandwidth estimation."
  ]
}